Helium is used over nitrogen to pressurize tanks because it's about 1/7th the mass at the same pressure and volume.  And mass is everything on a rocket.  Hydrogen would be lighter yet, but it's a really bad idea to pump hydrogen into your oxidizer tank. You could use it in the fuel tank, but then you need to manage two systems and two gasses instead of one. The mass savings probably aren't worth the extra complexity at that point.

I think the reason why just rocket lab has electric turbo pumps comes from the the electric equations.
The heating power in the motor AND your wires rise with the current squared. So double the current you have to size up wiring and hardware-cooling or size up by factor of four.
So either you rise your voltage in your batteries but that makes your electric controls and Hardware(like motor, switches, etc) LOTS more complicated and expensive. You do also need more weight and room for electric isolation.
So you (as always in life) end up with a compromise. For Electron it comes out OK because they need about 110Housepower(Tim said that) which is 80.9kW that's very OK and common for electric motors. But I think other (bigger) rockets need a LOT more pump-power to do their job.
And since room and weight are recources in rockets the best solution for them is to bet on combustion driven turbo pumps. That will someday change when other battery types are in charge(wordjoke) which have better capacity/weight ratio.
